    <div class="sec-t">About</div>
    <p>Östermalms Saluhall is a covered food market at Östermalmstorg in central Stockholm, opened in 1888 following construction over just six months. The building's brick facade was designed by architect Isak Gustaf Clason, while Kasper Salin engineered its cast-iron frame — a structural technique novel in Sweden at the time. King Oscar II officially inaugurated the hall that year. After a major renovation completed around 2020, the hall returned to its original location with a restored interior.</p>
    <p>The hall currently houses 17 specialist traders offering fresh seafood, smoked and pickled fish, artisan cheeses, cured meats, game meats including reindeer and elk, baked goods, chocolates, fresh produce and Swedish delicatessen. Several restaurants and counter-service bars operate within the hall, including long-standing traders such as Lisa Elmqvist Fisk and Nybroe Smørrebrød. The interior features carved wooden stall fittings characteristic of the original 1888 design.</p>
    <p>Entry to the hall is free at all times during opening hours. Visitors pay only for food and goods purchased directly from individual traders or restaurants. The hall is located a short walk from Humlegården park and the Army Museum (Armémuseet). Nearest metro access is Östermalmstorg on the red T-bana line. Bus lines 1, 66 and 91 stop at Nybrogatan; tram 7 serves Nybroplan approximately 600 metres away. Last updated: March 2026 · Verified</p>
